\n|change  = -8.51\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 37,326\n|percentage  = 72.78\n|change  = +2.73\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors\n|reg. electors = 51,283\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n|winner     = Conservative Party (UK) \n|swing = -4.26\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Elections in the 1970s===\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1970 United Kingdom general election|General election 1970]]:Ealing South <ref name=\"Craig50-73\"/><ref name=\"PolRes70\">{{cite web|last1=Kimber|first1=Richard|title=UK General Election results 1970 |url=http://politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge70/i07.htm|website=Political Science Resources|accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Conservative Party (UK) \n|candidate  = [[Brian Batsford]]\n|votes  = 19,326\n|percentage  = 54.98\n|change  = +4.16\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Cyril Rofe\n|votes  = 12,042\n|percentage  = 34.26\n|change  = -2.94\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Graham D Smith \n|votes  = 3,784\n|percentage  = 10.76\n|change  = -1.22\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 7,284\n|percentage  = 20.72\n|change  = +7.10\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 35,152\n|percentage  = 65.36\n|change  = -7.42\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors\n|reg. electors = 53,779\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n|winner     = Conservative Party (UK) \n|swing = +3.55\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|e|1|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ealing South (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in London (historic)]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1950]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies disestablished in 1974]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Ealing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox UK constituency\n|name       = Ealing South\n|type       = Borough\n|parliament = uk\n|year       = 1950\n|abolished  = February 1974\n|elects_howmany = one\n|previous   = [[Ealing East (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing East]]\n|next       = [[Acton (UK Parliament constituency)|Acton]] (major additions to)<br>[[Ealing North (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing North]] (minor additions to)<ref>(S.I. 1970 number 1674), at page 5491 (or 48 of 76)</ref>\n|}}\n'''Ealing South''' was a [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] covering the same part of the [[Municipal Borough of Ealing]] in [[Middlesex]] as its short-lived forerunner [[Ealing East (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing East]].  It returned one [[Member of Parliament|member]] (MP) to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]].  It was won by two Conservatives consecutively with majorities ranging from 13.6% to 30.5%, was first contested in the general election [[1950 United Kingdom general election|in 1950]] and was replaced before [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|that of February 1974]].\n\n==History==\nThe constituency was created for the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 general election]], and abolished for the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]]. In a repeat of the outcome of its direct forerunner Ealing East and its larger precursor in turn, [[Ealing (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing]] created in 1885, it was won by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] standing. The runner-up at each election was the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate, as with its predecessors since 1924 inclusive.\n\n==Boundaries==\n[[Image:Ealing London UK labelled ward map 2002.svg|thumb|This area was equivalent to mid-easterly London Borough Ealing wards (Ealing Broadway and those touching plus Northfield, less Elthorne which was largely a renamed Hanwell South)]]\nThis was a seat covering the same parts of the [[Municipal Borough of Ealing]] in [[Middlesex]] as its short-lived forerunner [[Ealing East (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing East]].\n\nThroughout (1950-1974): the [[Ealing Urban District|Ealing M.B.]] six [[wards of the United Kingdom|wards]]: Castlebar, Drayton, Grange Grosvenor, Lammas, Manor, and Mount Park.<ref>Representation of the People Act 1948, Sch. 1, at Middlesex (B) Borough Constituencies (page 108) http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1948/65/pdfs/ukpga_19480065_en.pdf</ref><ref>Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 1970 (S.I. 1970 number 1674), Sch I (list of contents of pre-existing) at page 5456 (or 13 of 76)</ref>\n\nAs to local government body from 1965 its components became part of the [[London Borough of Ealing]] in west [[London]].\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Election!!Member!!Party\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]]\n| [[Angus Edmund Upton Maude|Angus Maude]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1958 Ealing South by-election|1958 by-election]]\n| [[Brian Caldwell Cook Batsford|Brian Batsford]]\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"| [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|Feb 1974]]\n|colspan=\"2\"| ''constituency abolished''\n|}\n\n==Elections==\n''For 1945 see [[Ealing East (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing East]]''\n\n=== Elections in the 1950s ===\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1950 United Kingdom general election|General election 1950]]:Ealing South <ref name=\"Craig50-73\">British parliamentary election results, 1950-1973 by FWS Craig</ref><ref name=\"PolRes50\">{{cite web|last1=Kimber|first1=Richard|title=UK General Election results February 1950|url=http://politicsresources.net/area/uk/ge50/i07.htm|website=Political Science Resour